### Test 1: Check if admin email is taken (should return false)
GET http://localhost:8080/api/auth/check-email?email=admin@ecommerce.com

### Test 2: Check if new email is available (should return true)
GET http://localhost:8080/api/auth/check-email?email=brandnew@example.com

### Test 3: Register a new user
POST http://localhost:8080/api/auth/register
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "email": "tarunthakur.codes@gmail.com",
  "password": "IAMtannu@1",
  "firstName": "Tarun",
  "lastName": "Thakur",
  "phoneNumber": "+18622376821"
}

### Test 4: Login with the newly registered user
POST http://localhost:8080/api/auth/login
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "email": "tarunthakur.codes@gmail.com",
  "password": "IAMtannu@1"
}

### Test 5: Login with existing customer (from our sample data)
POST http://localhost:8080/api/auth/login
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "email": "customer@example.com",
  "password": "customer123"
}

### Test 6: Login with admin (from our sample data)
POST http://localhost:8080/api/auth/login
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "email": "admin@ecommerce.com",
  "password": "admin123"
}

### Test 7: Try login with wrong password (should fail)
POST http://localhost:8080/api/auth/login
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "email": "customer@example.com",
  "password": "wrongpassword"
}

### Test 8: Try to register with existing email (should fail)
POST http://localhost:8080/api/auth/register
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "email": "admin@ecommerce.com",
  "password": "password123",
  "firstName": "Duplicate",
  "lastName": "User"
}